What tho’ no weeping Loves thy ashes grace, Nor polish’d marble emulate thy face? What tho' no sacred earth allow thee room, Nor hallow'd dirge be mutter’d o’er thy tomb? Yet shall thy grave with rising flow’rs be drest‚ And thc green carrlia lightly on thy breast: There shall the morn her earliest tears bestow‚ There the first roses of the year shall blow; While Angels with their silver wings o’ershade The ground, now sacred by thy reliques made. So peaceful rests, without a stone, a name, What once had beauty, titles, wealth, and fame.
